[The Bronx has a wonderful botanical garden, a great zoo, its own
charming Little Italy]1 [(on Arthur Avenue)]2 [and, of course, the
Yankees.]3 [However, most people,]4 [having been subjected to news
footage of the devastated South Bronx,]5 [look at the borough the
way]6 [Tom Wolfe's Sherman McCoy did in "Bonfire of the Vanities"]7
[-- as a wrong turn into hell.]8

[But Laura Cunningham's Bronx, her childhood Bronx of the '50s, is
something else altogether.]9 [In a lovely, novelistic memoir,
"Sleeping Arrangements"]10 [(Knopf, 195 pages, $18.95),]11 [she
remembers an exotic playground,]12 [peopled mainly by Jewish
eccentrics and the occasional Catholic]13 [(real oddballs like her
sexpot friend, the hell-kitten Diana, age five).]14

[Ms. Cunningham, a novelist and playwright, has a vivid and
dramatically outsized sense of recall.]15 [She transforms her "Bronx
of the emotions, a place]16 [where the flats of mediocrity are only
relieved by steep descents into hysteria"]17 [into the "Babylonian
Bronx," a world]18 [simmering with sex and death and intrigue.]19 [In
the Babylonian Bronx, Jewish working-class people lived in drab,
Soviet-style buildings]20 ["glamorized" with names like AnaMor
Towers]21 [(after owners Anna and Morris Snezak),]22 [whose lobbies
and hallways were decorated with murals of ancient Syrians and Greeks,
